jor phonetic and phonological phenomena in modern Japanese by reviewing important studies in the fields over the past century. It also presents a summary of interesting questions that remain unsolved in the literature. The volume consists of eighteen chapters in addition to an introduction to the whole volume. In addition to providing descriptive generalizations of empirical phonetic/phonological facts, this volume also aims to give an overview of major phonological theories including, but not restricted to, traditional generative phonology, lexical phonology, prosodic morphology, intonational phonology, and the more recent Optimality Theory. It also touches on theories of speech perception and production. This book serves as a comprehensive guide to Japanese phonetics and phonology for all interested in linguistics and speech sciences.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aJapanese languagexPhoneticsvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aJapanese languagexPhonetics. 0aJapanese languagexPhonologyvHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aJapanese languagexPhonology. 4aJapanese. 4aPhonetics. 4aPhonology. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aKubozono, Haruo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2015z9783110438710oZDB-23-DSP0 cEPUBz97815015005960 cprintz978161451252340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978161451198440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781614511984423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cov